the specified hunting pressure (20 foragers) and environmental conditions, megaherbivore populations cannot sustain reproductive momentum beyond approximately 4.5-5 years (ticks 1600-1800), leading to demographic collapse.\n\nFor decision makers, the data indicate a critical tipping point around year 4-5 where populations transition from growth to decline. Management strategies must address hunting pressure thresholds that trigger post-peak collapse, as the system demonstrates limited demographic resilience. The pronounced seasonality creates predictable windows of reproductive vulnerability that may require targeted protection periods to prevent the observed 80% reduction in birth rates observed in later simulation phases."
